We are talking about a certain social construct that affects many aspects of life, from political leadership, business management, religious institutions, economic systems and property ownership, right down to the family home. It shows its monstrous form in unequal wages that stop equal access to opportunities, unequal distribution of household tasks and the like.

I have been challenging this notion since the 8th century, right about the time when I was born. Still confused? 13.9414° N, 121.6234° E shall be your friend. I have done my part by trying to limit his movements in the limited space that I have.
fields.modal: My popularity has soared in recent times in spite of me having just 64 squares.

fields.question:
Evan has a list of numbers. He asks his friends to assign points to each number, depending on whether they like the number, dislike it or don’t really have an opinion. If someone likes a number, that number is assigned a point of 1, if someone dislikes a number, then the number is assigned a point of 0. If someone is neutral about the number, it is not assigned any point.

Evan supplies you with a list of numbers that is liked by exactly as many people as it is disliked by(i.e it has been assigned 1 exactly as many times as it has been assigned 0):
2,9,10,37,52,56
Now, Evan supplies you with a bigger list. For each number in this list, you have to find whether it is liked by exactly as many people as it is disliked by. If the number has exactly as many lovers as haters, output Y, else output N. Note that neutral opinions( no points assigned) don't matter.
fields.modal: For eg: if a,b,c,d are the numbers and a and d have equal number of likes and dislikes, but b and c have unequal number of likes and dislikes, the answer is YNNY.
